          "title": "The disguise that failed — sovereignty over the random arrow",
          "body": "Ahab's scheme of disguise is the chapter's final act of defiance against the prophetic word. If the king of Israel cannot be identified, the word spoken against the king of Israel cannot find its mark — or so the logic runs. The Aramean commanders, looking for Ahab, nearly kill Jehoshaphat (22:32) — who is wearing the royal robes Ahab requested — before recognizing the error (22:33). Then verse 34 delivers the chapter's most theologically loaded sentence: 'a certain man drew his bow at random (*betom*).' The Hebrew *betom* means 'in simplicity,' 'without taking special aim' — the narrator is at pains to exclude any human intentionality from the fatal shot. The arrow finds the joint between the plates of Ahab's armor not by skill or design but by the precise sovereign governance of the God whose decree was issued at the heavenly throne before the battle was joined. No disguise, no human strategy, no political manipulation of prophets, and no imprisonment of the messenger changes a word already spoken. The image is indelible: a king propped up in his chariot all day (22:35), facing the enemy he is too wounded to fight, dying at evening, blood pooling in the chariot floor — the slow unfolding of a judgment that was never going to miss its mark."
